      Musk Twitter stuff
   =20
 =20

Yes, well,  clearly:

Twitter Inc. shareholders approved the $44 billion takeover that Elon Musk =
is trying to abandon on the same day that a whistleblower alleged at a hear=
ing on Capitol Hill that the social-media company misled regulators about s=
ecurity failures. =E2=80=A6
Twitter shareholders approved the takeover offer, with 98.6% of votes cast =
at a special meeting in favor of the deal, based on a preliminary tally of =
votes, the company said after polling closed Tuesday.

We   talked about this yesterday;=C2=A0I said it would be pretty silly to v=
ote against the deal. And in fact almost no one did. Only about  60% of Twi=
tter=E2=80=99s shares voted at all, but that was plenty to approve the deal=
. It is not immediately clear to me whether Elon Musk voted his shares in f=
avor of the merger, as he was obligated to do under the merger agreement (u=
nless he has terminated the agreement (which he says he has (though Twitter=
 says he hasn=E2=80=99t))), but he certainly didn=E2=80=99t vote=C2=A0again=
st=C2=A0the merger, and anyway it doesn=E2=80=99t matter either way.
Still, about 4.1 million shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0about $173 million worth =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0voted against the deal. Why? I guess you could tell a couple of=
=C2=A0stories. One is, you=E2=80=99re a Twitter shareholder because you bel=
ieve in the long-term value of the company. You think that it has a huge op=
portunity to make a ton of money, and that its current management has the a=
bility to execute against that opportunity. You have built a financial mode=
l and it says that Twitter is worth $70 per share, based on the discounted =
value of its expected (by you) future cash flows. So you don=E2=80=99t want=
 to sell to Elon Musk at $54.20; you want to keep your shares in this valua=
ble company. All very possible. Very much a minority opinion! But 1.4% of s=
hareholders=C2=A0might think this, sure.
  [6]

The other is, you=E2=80=99re a Twitter shareholder and also have some sort =
of socially-responsible-investing view. Perhaps you have a mandate to pursu=
e the best interests of all stakeholders in the companies you invest in. Pe=
rhaps you are an individual investor and you want to do good with your mone=
y. Perhaps you are a diversified index-y investor and you think a lot about=
 the systemic effects of your investment. In any case, you evaluate the sit=
uation holistically, and you say =E2=80=9Cwell, sure, Twitter is worth less=
 than $54.20, but I think it will be bad=C2=A0for the world=C2=A0(or for Tw=
itter=E2=80=99s employees, its users, etc.) for Elon Musk to own it, so I a=
m going to vote against the deal.=E2=80=9D
  [7]

I suspect this is even more of a minority opinion.
  [8]
 We talk a lot around here =E2=80=94=C2=A0lots of people talk a lot=C2=A0ev=
erywhere =E2=80=94=C2=A0about socially responsible investing and ESG and st=
akeholder capitalism and the purpose of corporations. And certainly back wh=
en Elon Musk said he wanted to buy Twitter, he said he wanted to do it for =
social and philosophical reasons. You could imagine the shareholder vote be=
ing about people=E2=80=99s competing visions for Twitter as a product and a=
s a public service. But, nah.=C2=A0Twitter=E2=80=99s board, and its shareho=
lders, have   pretty consistently cared only about the money.
  [9]

Meanwhile here=E2=80=99s   what the hedge funds are up to:

Hedge funds including David Einhorn=E2=80=99s Greenlight Capital and Pentwa=
ter Capital Management are wagering that Elon Musk won=E2=80=99t get his wa=
y this time.=C2=A0
Musk, the world=E2=80=99s richest person and a renowned sparring partner wi=
th regulators over securities laws, is trying to back out of his agreement =
to buy Twitter Inc. for $44 billion. Several hedge funds have purchased sto=
ck, options or bonds -- speculating that Musk will lose a trial scheduled t=
o begin Oct. 17 in Delaware Chancery Court. =E2=80=A6
The law is clear, Einhorn told investors in a letter last month. And =E2=80=
=9Cif it were anyone other than Musk, we would handicap the odds of the buy=
er wiggling out of the deal to be much less than 5%,=E2=80=9D he said. ...
=E2=80=9CWe think that the incentive of the Delaware Chancery Court, the pr=
eeminent and most respected business court in the nation, is to actually fo=
llow the law and apply it here,=E2=80=9D Einhorn wrote.

Well, that=E2=80=99s fine, and I think I have been pretty clear around here=
 that (1) I also think the odds are against Musk and (2) this is definitely=
 definitely not investment advice, and if you are a hedge-fund analyst maki=
ng the case for buying Twitter and you=E2=80=99re showing your boss my colu=
mns, knock it off right now. But mostly I want to point out that, while som=
e hedge funds are making this bet, it is not exactly the market consensus. =
Twitter=E2=80=99s stock closed yesterday at $41.74. That probably implies b=
etter-than-even odds of the deal closing,
  [10]
 but not 95%.=C2=A0Some=C2=A0hedge funds are betting that Musk can=E2=80=99=
t get out of the deal, but the market has some doubts.

