10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">The Merge</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The idea of a blockchain is that you want to d=
o bank transfers without a bank. You want people to be able to do transacti=
ons, and have them confirmed, and have there be some canonical agreed list =
of the transactions, but you don=E2=80=99t want to trust some central party=
 to do it.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At a high level, the blockchain solution is to=
 confirm transactions by letting everyone keep a copy of the transaction le=
dger. And then the official ledger is based on consensus among=C2=A0people =
who have some demonstrated stake in the system. What that has often meant i=
n practice =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/29049995.262538/aHR0cHM6Ly9iaXRjb2luLm9yZy9iaXRjb2luLnBkZg/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB9c5558a7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">what it means in Bitcoin</a> and what it=
=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29049995.262=
538/aHR0cHM6Ly9ldGhlcmV1bS5vcmcvZW4vd2hpdGVwYXBlci8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB551d21a4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">originally meant in Ethereum</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0is =E2=
=80=9Cproof of work.=E2=80=9D What you do is, you buy a bunch of computers,=
 and you set them to work solving meaningless math problems, and whoever so=
lves the most math problems the fastest gets to confirm a block of Bitcoin =
transactions, and they are rewarded with some newly minted Bitcoins and the=
n everyone starts over solving more math problems to confirm more transacti=
ons. Buying the computers, and paying for the electricity to run them to so=
lve the math problems, demonstrates your commitment to Bitcoin: It would be=
 crazy to spend all that money on computers and electricity to confirm=C2=
=A0<em>fake=C2=A0</em>transactions, which would undermine the value of Bitc=
oin and thus of your investment.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footno=
te-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !im=
portant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is called =E2=80=9Cmining=E2=80=9D: You s=
pend money on computers and electricity, and then you are rewarded with new=
ly created Bitcoins. And there are people, and publicly traded companies, w=
ho are in the business of Bitcoin mining and thus of maintaining the Bitcoi=
n network.=C2=A0The inputs are electricity and the outputs are Bitcoin.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This was a clever innovation and has some impo=
rtant benefits. It lets you have a ledger that is maintained by people with=
 incentives to do the right thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0people you can trust =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0without knowing who they are. There is no pre-approved list of =
people who are allowed to maintain the Bitcoin ledger; anyone who buys enou=
gh computers and electricity can participate. It is <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29049995.262538/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMTMvY3J5cHRvLXdhbnRzLXNvbWUtc2Vj=
LXJ1bGVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MTQyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3N=
vdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDkxNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB25e58094" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  permissionless</a>. But becau=
se they have to buy all those computers and electricity, they have good inc=
entives to maintain the ledger in a good way.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there are some problems. The biggest is th=
at=C2=A0it uses a ton of electricity solving pointless math problems, which=
 seems wasteful both in environmental terms (you=E2=80=99re emitting a lot =
of carbon to generate all that electricity) and <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29049995.262538/aHR0cHM6Ly92aXRhbGlrLmNhL2dlb=
mVyYWwvMjAyMC8xMS8wNi9wb3MyMDIwLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf32141d4" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> also in economic terms</a> (the Bitcoin system is effectively payin=
g utility companies a lot of money to maintain its=C2=A0ledger).=C2=A0Devel=
opers of later blockchains realized that, if the point here is to have tran=
sactions confirmed by people with a demonstrated stake in the system, there=
 are easier ways to demonstrate a stake in the system.<a class=3D"footnote-=
index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; di=
splay: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> Most simply: If you have a lot of Bitcoins, you will want Bitcoin to b=
e valuable, and so you will want to confirm transactions honestly in order =
to keep Bitcoin valuable. Instead of proving that you have an economic stak=
e in the system by spending a lot of money on computers and electricity, yo=
u could prove that you have an economic stake in the system by spending a l=
ot of money=C2=A0<em>on Bitcoin</em>. If you have a lot of Bitcoin, that pr=
oves that you care about Bitcoin, so you get to participate in confirming t=
ransactions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, that is not how Bitcoin works, but it is=
 how Ethereum works starting, uh, today-ish. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29049995.262538/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMTMvd2hhdC1zLWV0aGVyZXV=
tLWV0aC1tZXJnZS1wcm9vZi1vZi1zdGFrZS1kaWZmZXJzLWZyb20tYml0Y29pbi1idGM_Y21waW=
Q9QkJEMDkxNDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZ=
XR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwOTE0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB15c91d86" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  Olga Kharif and David Pan report</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ethereum is about to get a makeover. The popul=
ar crypto network that runs Ether, the world=E2=80=99s second-most-valuable=
 digital currency, could morph as early as Sept. 14 into a configuration th=
at shakes up the entire crypto universe.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The long-anticipated software change, =E2=80=
=9Cthe Merge=E2=80=9D to crypto fans worldwide, will lower Ethereum=E2=80=
=99s energy use by 99%, silencing critics who dislike the blockchain for it=
s electricity consumption=E2=80=94enough to power Finland for a year by one=
 estimate. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ethereum=E2=80=99s new process will rely inste=
ad on what=E2=80=99s called proof of stake. It consumes very little power, =
because it doesn=E2=80=99t depend on miners. It does require entities calle=
d validators to put some skin in the game in the form of Ether coins. Staki=
ng, or putting coins in the pot, gives large Ether owners the right to add =
a block of transactions to the ledger; they=E2=80=99re rewarded with new Et=
her when they do so. All Ether tokens will now pay interest when placed int=
o staking wallets. The software upgrade is called the Merge because the exi=
sting Ethereum blockchain will combine with a parallel network that=E2=80=
=99s been running for almost two years to test the proof-of-stake concept.<=
/p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you have a lot of Ether, you can stake them=
 and be a validator and confirm transactions and get rewarded with addition=
al Ether. Or, if you have a smaller amount of Ether, you can delegate them =
to a validator: You hand them over to some validator that you trust, and th=
at validator can stake them and confirm transactions and get rewarded with =
additional Ether and give you some of them. In practice, it is natural for =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29049995.262538/aH=
R0cHM6Ly9jb2ludGVsZWdyYXBoLmNvbS9uZXdzL2NvaW5iYXNlLXdvdWxkLXJhdGhlci1zaHV0L=
WRvd24tc3Rha2luZy10aGFuLWVuYWJsZS1vbi1jaGFpbi1jZW5zb3JzaGlwLWJyaWFuLWFybXN0=
cm9uZw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB019c68c7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> big crypto exchanges</a=
> like Binance, Coinbase and Kraken=C2=A0to be in this business: They are h=
olding on to people=E2=80=99s Ether for them anyway, and they have a big ec=
onomic interest in Ether working well,=C2=A0so they might as well stake cus=
tomers=E2=80=99 coins, validate transactions, and share the staking rewards=
 with their customers.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The economic model here is a bit different fro=
m the Bitcoin=C2=A0proof-of-work model. In that model, professional miners =
basically buy electricity and turn it into Bitcoins. In this model, profess=
ional stakers, or their customers, basically buy Ether and turn it into mor=
e Ether. You take your Ether, you lock it up in an account at a financial s=
ervices firm for a while, and your Ether grows by some steady percentage. Y=
ou know: like interest. Kharif and Pan write:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But for investors, the advantage is that Ether=
 post-Merge will resemble more of a traditional financial asset that pays i=
nterest, like a bond or a certificate of deposit. That could entice hedge f=
unds, asset managers, and wealthy individuals who=E2=80=99ve stayed on the =
crypto sidelines so far. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To acolytes, staked Ether becomes like shares =
of stock that generate dividends or bonds that pay a yield. Ether=E2=80=99s=
 yield could be relatively attractive: Owners who stake their coins can get=
 about 4% now, and that=E2=80=99s expected to rise post-Merge. As much as 8=
0% of all Ether supply=E2=80=94 about $170 billion at current prices=E2=80=
=94could eventually be staked, according to ConsenSys, an Ethereum blockcha=
in technology provider. =E2=80=9CI think that Ethereum=E2=80=99s merge fund=
amentally changes the asset,=E2=80=9D says Jack Neureuter, research analyst=
 at Fidelity Digital Assets, a unit of Fidelity Investments Inc. that plans=
 to offer custody and trading in Ether later this year. =E2=80=9CIt fundame=
ntally changes the investment case around it.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, for existing Ether investors, staked co=
ins will be similar to putting money to work instead of stuffing it under a=
 mattress. The yield feature allows traditional finance professionals who=
=E2=80=99ve long struggled with valuing crypto assets to perform cash-flow =
analyses to compare Ether=E2=80=99s performance with that of traditional as=
sets. They can also benchmark staked Ether against other investments. =E2=
=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not risk-free, but it gets you close,=E2=80=9D says Henr=
y Elder, head of decentralized finance at Wave Financial Group, an investme=
nt manager. =E2=80=9CThis is something that crypto really struggled with: H=
ow do you compare asset managers, how do you compare performance? I think t=
hat=E2=80=99s super important, because when you get to institutional invest=
ors, that=E2=80=99s the language that they speak.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In one sense, crypto is in the business of con=
stantly reinventing or rediscovering the basic ideas of financial history, =
and it is funny for crypto to reinvent=C2=A0<em>interest</em>. In another s=
ense this is=C2=A0cool: Crypto has rediscovered interest from entirely diff=
erent principles. In traditional finance, you get interest on your money be=
cause you are lending it to someone else to build some productive business.=
 In crypto, you get interest on your money because you are getting paid for=
 maintaining the ledger.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important;=
 background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A few notes. First, we talked a lot a few year=
s ago about Bitcoin futures. The idea of a Bitcoin futures contract is that=
 you get economic exposure to the price of Bitcoin without actually holding=
 a Bitcoin: For every dollar that the price of Bitcoin goes up, you get pai=
d $1 on your futures contract.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote=
-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impo=
rtant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0When Bitcoin futures contracts launched on traditional exchanges =
in 2017, the futures traded at a large premium to Bitcoin itself: People mi=
ght pay $18,000 for a Bitcoin but $18,500 for a Bitcoin future. I <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29049995.262538/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMTItMTkvYml0Y29pbi1m=
dXR1cmVzLWFyZS1hLWdyZWF0LXdheS10by1ub3Qtb3duLWJpdGNvaW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkxNDI=
yX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3=
Rlcm09MjIwOTE0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf9b=
d5e0a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">  explained this</a> by saying that, for a lot of traditiona=
l institutional investors, it was=C2=A0<em>much=C2=A0</em>more pleasant to =
hold a futures contract on a regulated exchange than it is to hold a Bitcoi=
n. If you own a Bitcoin, you=E2=80=99ll probably lose your private keys or =
get hacked or something; your compliance department and regulators won=E2=
=80=99t know what to make of it. If you own a futures contract on an exchan=
ge, that=E2=80=99s fine, that=E2=80=99s a normal thing, your systems and la=
wyers and regulators know how to handle that. So=C2=A0traditional investors=
 who wanted to get into Bitcoin would buy futures, and more nimble hedge fu=
nds would sell them the=C2=A0futures and buy Bitcoin to hedge, and the hedg=
e funds would get paid a premium because they were doing valuable work.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This effect has reduced over time, as institut=
ions have gotten more comfortable and=C2=A0efficient about owning crypto. A=
nd with=C2=A0staking it=C2=A0reverses. If you own actual Ethereum, you can =
stake it and earn interest. If you own <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/29049995.262538/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9tYWNyb2NlcG=
hhbG9wb2Qvc3RhdHVzLzE1NjkzNzkxOTM0MzA4NzYxNjY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB457b=
b06c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> Ethereum futures</a>, you miss out on the interest. So spot =
Ethereum should be worth more than futures, and futures for near-term deliv=
ery should be worth more=C2=A0than futures for later delivery. Ethereum sho=
uld be in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29049995=
.262538/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZGlnaXRhbC1nYW1tYS5jb20vX2ZpbGVzL3VnZC9hZGM0ZTFfMjl=
lNDFkZmQzZTg5NGQyMWEyYzg1OGFiMjA3ZmZiNTcucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd515=
8f28" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> backwardation</a>=C2=A0rather than contango: The forward pri=
ce should decline over time, because owning Ether now (and getting interest=
) is more valuable than owning it later (and missing out). If you are a hed=
ge fund buying spot Ether and=C2=A0selling Ether futures to institutions, n=
ow you should pay=C2=A0them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, I said above that it is natural for bi=
g centralized crypto exchanges to be Ethereum stakers: They are keeping tra=
ck of customer money anyway, they care about the ecosystem, they=C2=A0have =
rails to pay staking rewards to customers, etc. But the exchanges have othe=
r incentives: They tend to be big regulated companies located in financial =
centers; their executives tend to be rich and want to stay that way and avo=
id prison. They are thus convenient subjects of regulation. Some people in =
crypto worry that letting them be in charge of confirming Ethereum transact=
ions will mean that the Ethereum ledger itself becomes too subject to regul=
ation. At the Financial Times, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/29049995.262538/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvODg1MThiYz=
UtM2FmNC00MWMzLTk5YjUtYzBjZDBiYTY5YWI5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB40d2bfcf" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> Scott Chipolina=C2=A0reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This problem has become clearer since the US T=
reasury=E2=80=99s Office of Foreign Assets Control (Ofac) last month impose=
d sanctions against Tornado Cash, an Ethereum-based platform that the gover=
nment accused of facilitating billions-worth of laundered crypto. The staun=
chest of crypto=E2=80=99s libertarian army had said the heavy hand of gover=
nment would prove ineffective against the kinds of =E2=80=9Csmart contracts=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 computer software designed to automate transactions =E2=
=80=94 that run on decentralised platforms. Yet, sanctions have proved effe=
ctive after all. In the weeks since Tornado Cash was targeted, transactions=
 on the platform nosedived.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That worry is bound to cross the minds of Ethe=
reum=E2=80=99s future guardians, including exchanges Binance and Coinbase, =
and staking platform Lido Finance. According to Nansen data, these companie=
s are already some of the biggest Ethereum staking players around, and thus=
 will be trusted to secure the network post-Merge. Last month, Coinbase chi=
ef executive Brian Armstrong said his exchange would likely quit the stakin=
g business before censoring the network.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As guardians of the Ethereum network, these en=
tities will have to decide whether or not to validate and process blocks of=
 transactions that may contain transactions coming from entities under sanc=
tions such as Tornado Cash. That hardly sounds like the censorship-resistan=
t utopia envisioned by the idealists =E2=80=94 although critics of bitcoin =
point out that the concentration of miners (who are overwhelmingly based in=
 certain countries such as the US and Russia) in that blockchain also amoun=
ts to a centralised system.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The idea is that if Coinbase and Binance are c=
onfirming all of the Ethereum transactions, and the US Treasury goes to the=
m and says =E2=80=9Chey don=E2=80=99t confirm any Ethereum transactions fro=
m the following list of Russian-affiliated addresses,=E2=80=9D they=E2=80=
=99ll do what Treasury says rather than risking unpleasantness with the US =
government. And so the Ethereum blockchain will become a policy arm of the =
US government (or other governments with power over stakers), like the doll=
ar financial system is. I am not so sure about this worry: As Chipolina not=
es, Bitcoin mining is also pretty concentrated, including in US public comp=
anies, and I suppose that the Treasury could lean on Bitcoin miners to excl=
ude Russian transactions too. But, sure. Centralization exposes crypto to m=
ore effective regulation; if a million anonymous users confirm transactions=
 then they=E2=80=99re hard to censor, but if six big exchanges confirm tran=
sactions then those exchanges will want to stay on the good side of regulat=
ors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose one more point is that if you are a =
big <em>US</em>-based crypto exchange and you are paying staking rewards on=
 Ethereum, does that make your offering a security that needs to be registe=
red under US Securities and Exchange Commission rules? An interest-paying c=
rypto lending product is probably a security, the SEC=C2=A0<a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29049995.262538/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMDgvbGVuZGluZy1iaXRjb2luc=
